<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Can any one enlighten me as to how any one can warn the world of an
&gt;approaching blackhole, if no one can see it, especially if it is only
&gt;a small one, say a pound coin size?
">

It is unlikely that such small black holes even exist. Probably the
smallest black holes found in nature would be stellar mass, which means
they would be a few kilometers across. The risk such an object
introduces to the Solar System is purely a function of its mass, nothing
related to being a black hole. In other words, a rogue star passing
through the Solar System would have essentially the same effect-
disrupting the existing orbits of the planets before passing out again.

It is possible that we could detect an approaching black hole by
measuring orbital perturbations in the outer planets (more precisely, we
definitely could do this, but might not notice the effect). Of course,
there's nothing we could do about it; we don't remotely have the
technology to deflect an object massing several times the Sun!

