I don't think so. Reading his paper the thin Keplerian disk coupled by
a weak magnetic field is used as a model to make the task analytically
tractable. I don't see how any relativistic plasma will sit in that
sort of cold frictionless particle Keplerian disk (a la Saturns rings)
in a strong GR turbulent magnetic environment nearest the BH.

Other models seem to favour a toroidal plasma close in to the BH
trapping and trapped in the magnetic field lines with strange things
happening over the poles and at or near the notional cylinder where
the classical magnetic field lines would have to exceed the speed of
light if corotating with the BH (or neutron star). Further out the
consensus appears to be that the accretion disk is geometrically thin
and in the equatorial plane. Numerical relativistic MHD simulations
are being done at present check ADS for detials.

It is certainly true that the spinning magnetic field can generate
radiation and electron positron pairs from the BHs angular momentum -
the idea dates back to Blandford &amp; Znajek. Relativistic jets emitted
from the poles are believed to be one manifestation. One thing that
might make an approaching Kerr BH detectable is that there would be a
characteristic periodic modulation with it spinning that might attract
the attention of deep pulsar searches. And possibly some traces of
radio emission where the relativisitic jets hit the interstellar
medium.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I need to find some figures on the expected infall time
&gt; for matter in an accretion disk (i.e. persistence time
&gt; for the disks of a non-accreting black hole).  I'll keep browsing.
">

They are thought to be moderately short - there is a lot of friction
in the inner accretion disk orbits.

And a part of the evidence for QSOs and AGNs being powered by
droppping matter into a black hole is that no other method can be
compact enough to explain the observed time variability. As a general
rule of thumb for incoherent emitters if something can change its
output significantly in a couple of days then it has to be physically
smaller than 2 light days across (or relativistically beamed towards
us). Also BHs can conservatively extract ~30% of rest mass energy from
infalling matter compared to the puny 0.1% extracted by nuclear fusion
in stars.

Most practitioners think that quiescent BHs that have scoured their
neighbourhood of gas and dust are then virtually invisible apart from
distorting the background of distant "fixed" stars or causing the odd
one to scintilate briefly through lensing effects (and also through
their gravitational influance on any stars that pass close by). There
are a lot of radio quiet galaxies in the universe today and many more
active ones looking back in time at high red shifts.

