To a very good approximation it is empty. BHs on a starvation diet but
still luminous are reckoned to consume around 10^-15 solar mass per
year ( ~10^15kg) or put another way more than 10^7 kg per second with
something less that 30% efficiency. Compared to the few microgrammes
that a BH in interstellar space can hope muster this is a huge
difference in luminosity.

Although the time constants are not easily available. There are
several papers that claim that magnetic drag is responsible for the
transfer of angular momentum outwards that allows the orbitting
accretion disk to fall into the black hole. There are also
observations of rapid flaring in binary BH systems with accretion
disks where one BH is though to periodically impact on the others
accretion disk at semi-regular intervals. See for example the slightly
garbled report at:
http://heasarc.nasa.gov/docs/xte/learning_center/discover_0601.html

I haven't checked the original reference to Nature in July last year,
but a popularised summary is online at:
http://www.space.com/scienceastronomy/060621_bhole_magnetic.html

You only have to look at the orbitting material video around the Crab
nebula pulsar to see that life is brutal and short once it is in the
accretion disk. It either goes down the plug hole or gets ejected in
the polar jets and away from the compact object. The best hope for
seeing something coming would probably be when it went through regions
of enhanced density like the bow shock of the heliopause or Kuiper
belt for instance.

And my guess based on what AGN radio galaxies look like is that if it
were detectable it would be by the hot spots where its relativistic
jets impact on the interstellar medium that would be brightest and not
the central engine.

