I suspect there wouldn't be the right conditions for planets to form.
That is generally assumed to happen in the same process that forms a
star. A black hole is an older system, which has presumably swept its
region clear of most gas and dust. An accretion disk shouldn't be able
to coalesce to planets because of the chaotic environment close to a
pair of large masses. In the case of a black hole, it seems more likely
that outer planets might survive the supernova of the progenitor star
and continue orbiting around the black hole.

A ring system is dynamically possible, but rings are not highly stable
or long-lived. I don't know that there is enough material to build a
ring system after the supernova that created the black hole, and I don't
think a lone black hole can support an accretion disk at all. So where
would the rings come from?

